I have a filter which specifically excludes issues related to a specific customer:
{quote}(assignee = currentuser() OR watcher = currentuser() OR reporter = currentuser()) AND status != Done AND (customer != TestCustomer)
{quote}
Upon activating this filter, I was surprised to see two unrelated issues disappear from my list. A little investigation revealed that the issues had no customer assigned to them. I do know a little SQL, however, and I guessed that the JIRA filter query language uses the SQL-style NULL to represent “no company assigned”. Indeed, the issues reappeared when I added an explicit check for NULL, err, EMPTY:
{quote}(assignee = currentuser() OR watcher = currentuser() OR reporter = currentuser()) AND status != Done AND (customer != TestCustomer OR customer is EMPTY)
{quote}
I would not have expected to need to know SQL-style NULL-handling semantics when writing a filter to view issues. I would expect an issue with an empty customer field to not be excluded by the “AND (customer != TestCustomer)” clause in the first query. Maybe implement an empty field as a customer with an empty string ""?

(Of course, there may be a way to express my query in the easy mode query interface, without having to learn a query language at all; if it can be done, then *I*’m the giddy goat.)

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-64115].
  {panel}

I had a filter which made reference to a specific customer:
{quote}(assignee = currentuser() OR watcher = currentuser() OR reporter = currentuser()) AND status != Done AND (customer != TestCustomer OR customer is EMPTY)
{quote}
I used this filter on my JIRA homepage and it worked well. Then we deleted that specific customer. Now the homepage says:
{quote}The filter configured for this gadget could not be retrieved. Please verify it is still valid on the +issue navigator+.
{quote}
Clicking through to the issue navigator gave me this informational message:
{quote}The option 'TestCustomer' for field 'customer' does not exist.
{quote}
I agree that there should be some notification that the filter needs editing, but I would prefer that it attempt to Do The Right Thing and interpret it according to logic. In this case, the deleted option is part of a not-equals operation, so we can safely assume that everything is not-equal to it. In other words, interpret it as the following:
{quote}(assignee = currentuser() OR watcher = currentuser() OR reporter = currentuser()) AND status != Done AND (*TRUE* OR customer is EMPTY)
{quote}
This kind of fallback logic may not always be so obvious to calculate, but it would be useful when you can. It also shouldn’t hurt anything, as (so far as I know) filters only apply to data searching/filtering/display. The worst case is that the fallback logic gets something wrong and displays too few items (which is still more useful than displaying none) or too many (which shouldn’t harm anything, as I hope JIRA’s permissions system (assuming one exists) doesn’t go through the filter engine). It’s not like filters can batch-delete issues…can they?

